This paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning techniques for modeling the content structure of texts. The paper discusses the use of Hidden Markov Models for learning content models from un-annotated documents, which is a common technique in the field of computational linguistics. The paper also applies these models to two tasks: information ordering and extractive summarization, which are both relevant to the field of natural language processing. Based on these factors, the most likely sub-category for this paper is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Other likely sub-categories include cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.IR (Information Retrieval), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
